@4907  = ~Song of Warding~
@5010   = ~CLERIC/RANGER: This character can use the abilities of a Cleric and a Ranger, though weapons are restricted to only those allowed by the Cleric's ethos.  This character may Specialize in any weapon a cleric can use.  Upon starting the game, this character will automatically become a kitted Woodscout of Mielikki, or, if an elf, a Forestwalker of Solonor Thelandira.  With the blessings of these forest deities, the Woodscout or Forestwalker may cast both cleric and druid spells of all levels.~
@5011   = ~Woodscout of Mielikki~
@5012   = ~Totem of Mielikki~
@5013   = ~This an ornate carved symbol of the goddess Mielikki. A ranger who accomplishes deeds that please Mielikki may find and use a symbol such as this to devote his or her future development to worship of the goddess.  Such an action should not be taken lightly - it will halt development in the ranger's previous specialty.  But those who put their faith in the Forest Queen by this means will be able to become a Woodscout, a secialized priest of Mielikki.

Woodscouts combine the abilities of rangers and clerics.  It is said that Mielikki has received a special dispensation from Silvanus to grant her Woodscouts access to powerful druidic magic, so that they might better protect nature and champion the cause of justice.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5014   = ~Forestwalker of Solonor Thelandira~
@5020   = ~Bladesinger~
@5021   = ~The Art of the Bladesong~
@5022   = ~Among the Elven nations there is an order of warriors who wield power matched by few.  Combining martial skill with magical prowess, Bladesingers have the resources to face nearly any threat.  They master the use of long blades wielded in one hand, keeping the other free for spellcasting.

Bladesingers begin at level 1 with proficiency in Single-Weapon Style.  At level 7, this automatically increases to specialization.  They may reach grandmastery with long swords, scimitars, and katanas, and may only reach basic proficiency with other one-handed weapons and missile weapons.  They may not become proficient with two-handed weapons or in any other fighting style.

Once per day per 6 levels, a bladesinger may perform the Bladesong, a dance in which a blade is spun and whirled faster than the eye can follow, blocking incoming attacks and devastating enemies.  Upon beginning the Bladesong, for 24 seconds, the bladesinger has a +1 bonus to thac0 per 5 levels, a -2 bonus to AC vs. melee attacks per five levels, one extra attack per round, faster movement rate, and all successful attacks do maximum damage.

The descriptions and instructions in this tome may enable an elf reading it to learn the skills and abilities of a Bladesinger.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5023   = ~Bladesong~
@5024   = ~BLADESONG: for 24 seconds, the bladesinger has a +1 bonus to thac0 per 5 levels, a -2 bonus to AC vs. melee attacks per five levels, one extra attack per round, faster movement rate, and all successful attacks do maximum damage.~
@5031   = ~Spellfilcher~
@5032   = ~Secrets of the Spellfilchers~
@5033   = ~The Spellfilchers are hidden society of very specialized thieves.  They hone their abilities toward a dangerous goal: stealing magic from wizards.  To that end, Spellfilchers have a few special tricks they can employ when confronted by angry mages.

First, they may cast the priest spell "Silence 15' Radius" to prevent an enemy from casting spells. Of course many wizards know the Vocalize spell to overcome such a disadvantage, but a skilled Spellfilcher knows that the time it takes to do so may make all the difference in the world.

Second, at 5th level Spellfilchers can cast a special variant of "Spell Turning" which lasts for 12 hours.  It will only turn back a single spell, but doing so may give a Spellfilcher the time he or she needs to get better spell protections up if surprised.  Spellfilchers commonly erect this protection every morning, before even brushing their teeth.

Third, at 9th level Spellfilchers become innately and permanently protected by the effect of the spell "Non-detection," enabling them to use their thiefly abilities to hide even from wizards with powerful scrying magic.

Finally, every time a Spellfilcher successfully strikes a wizard with a melee attack, the target must save vs. rods/wands or suffer a 33% chance of miscast magic for 2 rounds.

The secrets contained in this tome may enable the owner to learn the skills and abilities of a Spellfilcher.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5034   = ~Silence~
@5035   = ~All enemies in the area must make a saving throw vs. spell at -1; if the save is failed, then they are silenced for the duration of the spell, unless an affected spellcaster then casts Vocalize.  At the instant the spell is completed, it affects all creatures in a 15 foot radius centered on the point selected by the Spellfilcher.~
@5036   = ~Spell Turning~
@5037   = ~This abjuration causes one spell cast against the Spellfilcher to rebound upon the original caster.~
@5041   = ~Nightrunner of Mask~
@5042   = ~Totem of Mask~
@5043   = ~This an ornate carved symbol of Mask, a god of shadows, thievery, and deception.  Mask's Nightrunners are multiclass cleric/thieves who travel the land advancing Mask's agenda.  They are adept at hiding in shadows and can use their divine magical abilities to augment their thieving skills.

Mask grants his Nightrunners a few special abilities to advance his cause.  From first level, they may create a Shadow Eye, an invisible floating eye through which the Nightrunner can scout distant locations.  From 4th level, Nightrunners can suddenly disappear from sight via a magical Shadow Door.  And at 8th level, they gain the ability to conjure a creature of pure shadow to fight on their behalf.

With a totem such as this, a cleric/thief may devote oneself fully to the worship of Mask, becoming a Nightrunner in word and deed.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5044   = ~Shadow Eye~
@5045   = ~The Nightrunner creates an shadowy sensory organ that can move away and sends back visual information to the Nightrunner's mind. The Shadow Eye eye can see with normal vision up to 60 feet away in brightly lit areas, and travel in any direction as long as the spell lasts.~
@5046   = ~Shadow Door~
@5047   = ~By means of this spell, the Nightrunner creates the illusion of a door and steps through it, becoming totally invisible for the spell duration. Opponents within 5 feet of the caster must save vs. spell at -4 or be fooled into following the caster through the door, becoming trapped in an extradimensional room for up to 4 rounds.~
@5048   = ~Summon Shadow~
@5049   = ~This spell summons a shadow, an undead monster which will serve the Nightrunner under any conditions.~
@5050   = ~Shadow~
@5051  = ~Abilities:
- Major Access to the spheres of Divine Aid, Knowledge, Thought, Dread, Shadow, and Deception.
- Minor Access to the spheres of Life, Death, War, Protection. Vigor, Affliction, and Magic.~
@5060   = ~Misadventurer of Brandobaris~
@5061   = ~Totem of Brandobaris~
@5062   = ~This an ornate carved symbol of Brandobaris, halfling god of trickery and adventure.  His followers are cleric/thieves known as misadventurers.  They have an unusual tendency to get into trouble as they wander the land... but they also have a reputation for uncanny abilities to narrowly escape danger.  Their deeds are fraught with both peril and annoyance, but they are never boring!

Misadventurers are given special abilities by Brandobaris to get out of any trouble they may find themselves in.  First, they are very difficult to strike in battle, gaining a -1 bonus to AC for each 7 levels of experience.  Second, from 4th level they may Haste themselves to escape harm.  Finally, from 8th level they may create Scattering Images of themselves to confuse opponents.  When struck by a weapon, there is a chance that the blow will land on an illusory image, instead of upon the misadventurer.

With a totem such as this, a cleric/thief may devote oneself fully to the worship of Brandobaris, becoming one of his Misadventurers.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5063   = ~Haste~
@5064   = ~When this spell is cast, the Misadventurer moves at double the normal rate, gains a -2 initiative bonus, and receives an extra attack each round.~
@5065   = ~Scattering Images~
@5066   = ~Upon casting this spell, the wizard creates extra images of himself that will travel along beside him.  The images will perform all of the actions that the wizard does so that if any enemies are trying to attack the wizard they will not know which one is real.  There is a 50% chance that an attacker will attack an image, and a 50% chance that he will attack the caster.  The images will disappear with a successful dispel magic, when attacked, or when the spell duration runs out.~
@5067  = ~Abilities:
- Major Access to the spheres of Divine Aid, Life, Protection, Thought, Air, and Light.
- Minor Access to the spheres of Knowledge, Vigor, Animal, Shadow, Deception, and Magic.~
@5070   = ~Hearthguard of Arvoreen~
@5071   = ~Totem of Arvoreen~
@5072   = ~This an ornate carved symbol of Arvoreen, the halfling goddess of protection and militant defense.  Her followers, the Hearthguards, are multiclass fighter/clerics who use their formidable courage, training, and magic to protect halfling communities and interests from whatever threats may appear.

Hearthguards have innate abilities to rally their companions and remove magical fear; and to imbue themselves with divine strength; and to heal the injured by laying on hands like a paladin.  They may perform each such feat once per day per six levels of experience.

With a totem such as this, a fighter/cleric may devote oneself fully to the worship of Arvoreen, permanently joining the ranks of the Hearthguards.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5073  = ~Abilities:
- Major Access to the spheres of Divine Aid, Life, Protection, Vigor, War, and Light.
- Minor Access to the spheres of Knowledge, Thought, Animal, Plant, Earth, and Magic.~
@5080   = ~Alaghor of Clangeddin~
@5081   = ~Totem of Clangeddin~
@5082   = ~This an ornate carved symbol of the dwarven god Clangeddin Silverbeard.  Alaghors are his elite order of fighter/clerics.  They are powerful warriors as well as wise ministers, protecting dwarven communities from threats both physical and spiritual.

Alaghors share some abilities with the famed Dwarven Defenders, though they do not focus as much on melee durability.  Once per day, an Alaghor may use the Hardiness power, gaining 35% resistance to physical attacks for one round per two levels of experience.

Alaghors also have an innate ability to create a Spiritual Hammer of Clangeddin.  This weapon of magical force does d4+1 blunt damage and d4 magic damage to foes, and has a chance to briefly Hold undead struck by it. It is wielded as if the bearer is specialized (2 stars) in its use.  These abilities increase as the Alaghor rises in level.

With a totem such as this, a fighter/cleric may devote oneself fully to the worship of Clangeddin, gaining the power of an Alaghor.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5083   = ~Hammer of Clangeddin~
@5084   = ~This weapon of magical force does d4+1 blunt damage and d4 magic damage to foes, and has a chance to briefly Hold undead struck by it. It is wielded as if the bearer is specialized (2 stars) in its use.  These abilities increase as the Alaghor rises in level.~
@5085   = ~Hardiness~
@5086   = ~Calling upon hidden reserves of strength during times of danger, an Alaghor can use the Hardiness ability to gain 35% resistance to all forms of physical damage. The ability lasts for 5 rounds.~
@5087   = ~Hammer of Clangeddin~
@5088  = ~Abilities:
- Major Access to the spheres of Divine Aid, Protection, Destruction, War, Vigor, and Earth.
- Minor Access to the spheres of Life, Knowledge, Thought, Dread, and Light.~
@5090   = ~Gloryblood of Tempus~
@5091   = ~Totem of Tempus~
@5092   = ~This an ornate carved symbol of the god Tempus (or, as the northern barbarian tribes know him, Tempos). Known as the Lord of Battles and The Foehammer, Tempus is the god of war. No paladins honor him, but a sect of fighting clerics known as Glorybloods travel the Realms in search of battles to join. They revel in bloody struggle but also ensure that battles are conducted honorably.

Glorybloods have an innate ability to create a Spiritual Axe of Tempus. This weapon of magical force does d4+1 slashing damage and d4 magic damage to foes, and has a chance to cause Panic in anyone struck by it. It is wielded as if the bearer is specialized (2 stars) in its use. These abilities increase as the Gloryblood rises in level.

Glorybloods also have the ability to enter an enraged state, similar to a barbarian. This state lasts for 5 rounds, and grants the Gloryblood a +4 bonus to Strength and Constitution, a +2 bonus to saves vs. spells, a +2 penalty to AC, and immunity to charm, hold, fear, maze, stun, sleep, confusion, and level drain effects.

With a totem such as this, a fighter/cleric may devote oneself fully to the worship of Tempus, gaining the power of a Gloryblood.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5093  = ~Known as the Lord of Battles and The Foehammer, Tempus is the god of war. His dogma is primarily concerned with honorable battle, forbidding cowardice and encouraging the use of force of arms to settle disputes. Glorybloods travel the Realms in search of battles to join, to revel in the struggle but also to ensure they are conducted honorably.~
@5094  = ~GLORYBLOOD OF TEMPUS: Known as the Lord of Battles and The Foehammer, Tempus is the god of war. His dogma is primarily concerned with honorable battle, forbidding cowardice and encouraging the use of force of arms to settle disputes. Glorybloods travel the Realms in search of battles to join, to revel in the struggle but also to ensure they are conducted honorably.
 
Abilities:
- enter an enraged state, similar to a barbarian. This state lasts for 5 rounds, and grants the Gloryblood a +4 bonus to Strength and Constitution, a +2 bonus to saves vs. spells, a +2 penalty to AC, and immunity to charm, hold, fear, maze, stun, sleep, confusion, and level drain effects.
- May create a Spiritual Axe of Tempus. This weapon of magical force does d4+1 slashing damage and d4 magic damage to foes, and has a chance to cause Panic in anyone struck by it. It is wielded as if the bearer is specialized (2 stars) in its use. These abilities increase as the Gloryblood rises in level.

Restrictions:
- Alignment: may not be Lawful.
~
@5095  = ~Abilities:
- Major Access to the spheres of War, Divine Aid, Protection, Destruction, Dread, and Vigor.
- Minor Access to the spheres of Life, Death, Knowledge, Thought, and Earth.~
@5100  = ~monitor of mystra~
@5101  = ~Monitor of Mystra~
@5102  = ~Mystra is known as the Lady of Spells and the Mother of Magic. She tends to the Weave, which enables mortals to cast spells. Mystra's clerics, known as Monitors, watch over the different uses of magic power and prevent magical abuse.~
@5103  = ~Totem of Mystra~
@5104  = ~This an ornate carved symbol of the goddess Mystra. Known as the Lady of Spells and the Mother of Magic. She tends to the Weave, which enables mortals to cast spells. Mystra's clerics, known as Monitors, watch over the different uses of magic power and prevent magical abuse. 

Monitors are in tune with magical energies in a way that few spellcasters can match; they can create effects with a power level beyond their nominal experience. They effectively act as if their caster level is one higher than their experience level. This increases by one for each 4 levels of experience they gain.

Monitors may not cast wizard spells from the school of Necromancy.

With a totem such as this, a cleric/mage may devote oneself fully to the worship of Mystra, gaining the power of a Monitor.

[WARNING: activation of this item cannot be reversed.  Save before doing so.]~
@5105  = ~Abilities:
- Focus Access to the sphere of Magic.
- Major Access to the spheres of Divine Aid, Life, Protection, Destruction, Knowledge, and Light.
- Minor Access to the spheres of Thought, Dread, Vigor, Air, Fire, Shadow, and Deception.~
@5111  = ~Spellbender~
@5112  = ~The goddess Mystra rules the fabled Weave of Faerun, the ethereal conduit that allows mortals to shape magical energies into spells and effects. In order to avoid disasters like that which befell Anauroch, Mystra ensures that the use of those energies is strictly controlled: spellcasters must formulate the Weave into specific, known spells, and must memorize the patterns of those spells in order to successfully release them.

But, as with any rigid system, the are gaps and shortcuts that may be used to circumvent Mystra's rules. Sorcerers are born with the ability to focus the Weave directly, though only into a limited number of effects. Wild mages shape spells without discipline, achieving powerful results at the risk of disastrous side-effects.

Unlike those classes, Spellbenders make a science of mapping the ways to bypass Mystra's restrictions. Practicing as generalist clerics and studying arcane magery, they learn to manipulate the intersection of those two areas of magic. They may sacrifice a memorized wizard spell to instead create one of numerous divine effects; and they may sacrifice a memorized cleric spell to create an arcane effect. Some energy is lost in the translation - the improvisational effects must be spells of lower level than the one sacrificed. (It is unknown what happens to the lost energy - some believe this practice has contributed to the recent rise of wild magic and sorcerers. Spellbenders must be wary, as they are apt to be persecuted by Mystra's Monitors.)

While Spellbenders are not as powerful one-to-one as a Sorcerer or Wild Mage or Monitor, the studious application of their knowledge gives them precise control over the Weave that is unmatched by any other spellcaster.~
